The problem asks us to compute the ratio $N/M$ of two combinatorial quantities. $N$ counts switching sequences on $2n$ lamps where the first $n$ lamps end up ON and the rest OFF. $M$ counts sequences where additionally the last $n$ lamps are never switched ON.

We model the sequences of switches as functions $f : \text{Fin } k \to \text{Fin } (2n)$.
The condition for $N$ translates to: for each $i < n$, $f$ selects $i$ (or $i+n$) an odd number of times in total; for each $i \ge n$, the count is even. (More precisely, for a lamp $j$, the final state is ON iff the number of times $j$ is toggled is odd).
The condition for $M$ translates to: $f$ takes values only in $\{0, \dots, n-1\}$, and each $i < n$ is selected an odd number of times. (Lamps $n \dots 2n-1$ are never switched ON implies they are never toggled).

Let $S_N$ be the set of index sequences for $N$, and $S_M$ for $M$.
Consider the map $\pi: S_N \to S_M$ given by $\pi(f)(t) = f(t) \pmod n$.
For a sequence $f \in S_N$, let $c_j$ be the count of $j$ and $d_j$ be the count of $j+n$.
The final state conditions are: $c_j$ is odd, $d_j$ is even.
The projected sequence $\pi(f)$ has counts $k_j = c_j + d_j$.
Since odd + even = odd, $k_j$ is odd for all $j < n$. Thus $\pi(f) \in S_M$.
For a fixed $g \in S_M$, let $k_j$ be the count of $j$ in $g$. Note $\sum k_j = k$. Since $g \in S_M$, each $k_j$ is odd, so $k_j \ge 1$.
To lift $g$ to $f \in S_N$, for each occurrence of $j$ in $g$, we must choose whether $f$ takes value $j$ or $j+n$.
If $j$ occurs $k_j$ times, we choose a subset of these positions to be $j+n$ (count $d_j$) and the rest $j$ (count $c_j$).
We need $c_j$ odd and $d_j$ even. Since $c_j + d_j = k_j$ is odd, $d_j$ even $\iff c_j$ odd.
So we essentially need to choose a subset of size $c_j$ where $c_j$ is odd.
The number of odd-sized subsets of a set of size $k_j \ge 1$ is $2^{k_j - 1}$.
We do this independently for each $j \in \{0, \dots, n-1\}$.
The size of the fiber is $\prod_{j=0}^{n-1} 2^{k_j - 1} = 2^{\sum k_j - n} = 2^{k - n}$.
Thus $|S_N| = 2^{k-n} |S_M|$, so $N = 2^{k-n} M$.
The ratio is $2^{k-n}$.

