The problem asks for the ratio $N/M$ of two counts of switching sequences. We model the sequences as functions $u : \text{Fin } k \to \text{Fin } (2n)$ (indicating which lamp is switched at each step).
The state of lamp $j$ after $k$ steps is ON if it was switched an odd number of times, OFF otherwise.
$N$ counts sequences where lamps $1..n$ are odd, $n+1..2n$ are even.
$M$ counts sequences where lamps $1..n$ are odd, $n+1..2n$ are never switched (count is 0).

We use the method of exponential generating functions / derivatives.
The number of sequences with specific parity constraints is given by extracting coefficients from products of $\sinh(x)$ and $\cosh(x)$.
Specifically, $N$ is related to the $k$-th derivative of $(\sinh x)^n (\cosh x)^n$ at 0.
$M$ is related to the $k$-th derivative of $(\sinh x)^n$ at 0.
Using the identity $(\sinh x \cosh x)^n = 2^{-n} (\sinh 2x)^n$, we derive $N = 2^{k-n} M$.

