The problem asks to calculate the ratio $N/M$. $N$ counts switching sequences of length $k$ on $2n$ lamps starting from all off, ending with $1..n$ on and $n+1..2n$ off. $M$ counts such sequences where lamps $n+1..2n$ are never switched on.

We identify switching sequences with index sequences $f: \text{Fin } k \to \text{Fin }(2n)$. The condition for $N$ translates to: the count of each $i \in \{1..n\}$ is odd, and the count of each $i \in \{n+1..2n\}$ is even. The condition for $M$ translates to: the indices are in $\{1..n\}$ and the count of each $i \in \{1..n\}$ is odd.

Let $U$ be the set of valid index sequences for $N$, and $V$ for $M$.
There is a projection $\pi: U \to V$ mapping $f \mapsto (t \mapsto f(t) \pmod n)$.
For any $g \in V$, the fiber $\pi^{-1}(g)$ has size $2^{k-n}$. This is because for each time $t$ where $g(t) = i$, we can choose $f(t) = i$ or $f(t) = i+n$. For a fixed $i$, if it appears $c_i$ times in $g$ ($c_i$ is odd), we need to choose $i$ an odd number of times. The number of such choices is $2^{c_i-1}$. Summing $c_i - 1$ over all $i$ gives $k-n$.
Thus $|U| = 2^{k-n} |V|$. Since $N = |U|$ and $M = |V|$, $N/M = 2^{k-n}$.

