To solve the problem, we define a projection mapping from the set of valid sequences $S_N$ to the set of valid sequences $S_M$.
For a history $s \in S_N$, we define $P(s)$ such that for each lamp $i \in \{0, \dots, n-1\}$, the state of $i$ in $P(s)$ is the XOR sum of the states of $i$ and $i+n$ in $s$.
We show that $P$ maps $S_N$ to $S_M$.
For any $v \in S_M$, we calculate the size of the fiber $P^{-1}(v)$. The degrees of freedom correspond to choosing, for each time step where lamp $i$ is switched in $v$, whether to switch $i$ or $i+n$ in $s$. The parity constraints on the final state of $s$ (specifically that lamp $i+n$ ends up OFF) impose exactly one linear constraint on these choices for each $i$.
Since lamp $i$ is switched an odd number of times in $v$ (because $v \in S_M$), the number of choices for each $i$ is $2^{k_i - 1}$ where $k_i$ is the number of switches.
Summing over all $i$ gives the total fiber size $2^{k-n}$.

