The problem asks for the ratio $N/M$. We analyze the combinatorial definitions of $N$ and $M$.

$M$ counts the number of switching sequences of length $k$ involving $n$ lamps (labeled $1$ to $n$) such that all lamps end up ON. Since they start OFF, each lamp must be switched an odd number of times. The condition that lamps $n+1 \dots 2n$ are never switched on implies they are never toggled, so we effectively only use lamps $1 \dots n$.

$N$ counts the number of switching sequences of length $k$ involving $2n$ lamps such that lamps $1 \dots n$ end up ON (odd switches) and lamps $n+1 \dots 2n$ end up OFF (even switches).

We map a sequence in $N$'s set to a sequence in $M$'s set by identifying lamp $i$ and lamp $n+i$. Specifically, if a step toggles $i$ or $n+i$, we map it to a toggle of $i$.
For a fixed sequence in $M$'s set (where each lamp $i \in \{1 \dots n\}$ is toggled $r_i$ times, with $r_i$ odd), we want to lift it to a sequence in $N$'s set. For each of the $r_i$ toggles of lamp $i$, we can choose to toggle either $i$ or $n+i$. Let $x$ be the number of times we toggle $n+i$. We require $x$ to be even. The number of subsets of size $r_i$ with even cardinality is $2^{r_i-1}$ (since $r_i \ge 1$).
The total number of liftings is the product over all $i=1 \dots n$ of $2^{r_i-1}$.
$\prod_{i=1}^n 2^{r_i-1} = 2^{\sum r_i - n} = 2^{k-n}$.
Thus $N = M \cdot 2^{k-n}$.

